e 3:**\n\nInput: differences = [4,-7,2], lower = 3, upper = 6\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There are no possible hidden sequences. Thus, we return 0.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == differences.length`\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `-10⁵ <= differences[i] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `-10⁵ <= lower <= upper <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/count-the-hidden-sequences/","problemName":"Count the Hidden Sequences","problemNumber":2145,"problemSlug":"count-the-hidden-sequences","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2145,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[{"assetIndex":0,"bytes":11537,"contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example1drawio.png","originalUrl":"../../../images/2146-example1drawio.png","sha256":"cc845a314d44d3d705a610f1251bedb170758532f187c326695d72169db764c2"},{"assetIndex":1,"bytes":12004,"contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example2drawio1.png","originalUrl":"../../../images/2146-example2drawio1.png","sha256":"105130572eb8c527ec5311b049cb447d555a252644d68308c5c967b5b1023058"},{"assetIndex":2,"bytes":8557,"contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example3.png","originalUrl":"../../../images/2146-example3.png","sha256":"5571ce2a6d61c7714e7cb4d431802bea60641d031d39ef508778b433c96857f4"}],"categories":["Array","Breadth-First Search","Sorting","Heap (Priority Queue)","Matrix"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given a **0-indexed** 2D integer array `grid` of size `m x n` that represents a map of the items in a shop. The integers in the grid represent the following:\n\n- `0` represents a wall that you cannot pass through.\n\n- `1` represents an empty cell that you can freely move to and from.\n\n- All other positive integers represent the price of an item in that cell. You may also freely move to and from these item cells.\n\nIt takes `1` step to travel between adjacent grid cells.\n\nYou are also given integer arrays `pricing` and `start` where `pricing = [low, high]` and `start = [row, col]` indicates that you start at the position `(row, col)` and are interested only in items with a price in the range of `[low, high]` (**inclusive**). You are further given an integer `k`.\n\nYou are interested in the **positions** of the `k` **highest-ranked** items whose prices are **within** the given price range. The rank is determined by the **first** of these criteria that is different:\n\n- Distance, defined as the length of the shortest path from the `start` (**shorter** distance has a higher rank).\n\n- Price (**lower** price has a higher rank, but it must be **in the price range**).\n\n- The row number (**smaller** row number has a higher rank).\n\n- The column number (**smaller** column number has a higher rank).\n\nReturn *the *`k`* highest-ranked items within the price range **sorted** by their rank (highest to lowest)*. If there are fewer than `k` reachable items within the price range, return ***all** of them*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example1drawio.png","sequence":1,"sha256":"cc845a314d44d3d705a610f1251bedb170758532f187c326695d72169db764c2","type":"image"},{"sequence":2,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,2,0,1],[1,3,0,1],[0,2,5,1]], pricing = [2,5], start = [0,0], k = 3\nOutput: [[0,1],[1,1],[2,1]]\nExplanation: You start at (0,0).\nWith a price range of [2,5], we can take items from (0,1), (1,1), (2,1) and (2,2).\nThe ranks of these items are:\n- (0,1) with distance 1\n- (1,1) with distance 2\n- (2,1) with distance 3\n- (2,2) with distance 4\nThus, the 3 highest ranked items in the price range are (0,1), (1,1), and (2,1).","type":"code"},{"sequence":3,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example2drawio1.png","sequence":4,"sha256":"105130572eb8c527ec5311b049cb447d555a252644d68308c5c967b5b1023058","type":"image"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,2,0,1],[1,3,3,1],[0,2,5,1]], pricing = [2,3], start = [2,3], k = 2\nOutput: [[2,1],[1,2]]\nExplanation: You start at (2,3).\nWith a price range of [2,3], we can take items from (0,1), (1,1), (1,2) and (2,1).\nThe ranks of these items are:\n- (2,1) with distance 2, price 2\n- (1,2) with distance 2, price 3\n- (1,1) with distance 3\n- (0,1) with distance 4\nThus, the 2 highest ranked items in the price range are (2,1) and (1,2).","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"alt":"Problem image","contentType":"image/png","localPath":"leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example3.png","sequence":7,"sha256":"5571ce2a6d61c7714e7cb4d431802bea60641d031d39ef508778b433c96857f4","type":"image"},{"sequence":8,"text":"Input: grid = [[1,1,1],[0,0,1],[2,3,4]], pricing = [2,3], start = [0,0], k = 3\nOutput: [[2,1],[2,0]]\nExplanation: You start at (0,0).\nWith a price range of [2,3], we can take items from (2,0) and (2,1). \nThe ranks of these items are: \n- (2,1) with distance 5\n- (2,0) with distance 6\nThus, the 2 highest ranked items in the price range are (2,1) and (2,0). \nNote that k = 3 but there are only 2 reachable items within the price range.","type":"code"},{"sequence":9,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= m * n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= grid[i][j] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `pricing.length == 2`\n\n- `2 <= low <= high <= 10⁵`\n\n- `start.length == 2`\n\n- `0 <= row <= m - 1`\n\n- `0 <= col <= n - 1`\n\n- `grid[row][col] > 0`\n\n- `1 <= k <= m * n`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Breadth-First Search","Sorting","Heap (Priority Queue)","Matrix"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given a **0-indexed** 2D integer array `grid` of size `m x n` that represents a map of the items in a shop. The integers in the grid represent the following:\n\n- `0` represents a wall that you cannot pass through.\n\n- `1` represents an empty cell that you can freely move to and from.\n\n- All other positive integers represent the price of an item in that cell. You may also freely move to and from these item cells.\n\nIt takes `1` step to travel between adjacent grid cells.\n\nYou are also given integer arrays `pricing` and `start` where `pricing = [low, high]` and `start = [row, col]` indicates that you start at the position `(row, col)` and are interested only in items with a price in the range of `[low, high]` (**inclusive**). You are further given an integer `k`.\n\nYou are interested in the **positions** of the `k` **highest-ranked** items whose prices are **within** the given price range. The rank is determined by the **first** of these criteria that is different:\n\n- Distance, defined as the length of the shortest path from the `start` (**shorter** distance has a higher rank).\n\n- Price (**lower** price has a higher rank, but it must be **in the price range**).\n\n- The row number (**smaller** row number has a higher rank).\n\n- The column number (**smaller** column number has a higher rank).\n\nReturn *the *`k`* highest-ranked items within the price range **sorted** by their rank (highest to lowest)*. If there are fewer than `k` reachable items within the price range, return ***all** of them*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example1drawio.png]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,2,0,1],[1,3,0,1],[0,2,5,1]], pricing = [2,5], start = [0,0], k = 3\nOutput: [[0,1],[1,1],[2,1]]\nExplanation: You start at (0,0).\nWith a price range of [2,5], we can take items from (0,1), (1,1), (2,1) and (2,2).\nThe ranks of these items are:\n- (0,1) with distance 1\n- (1,1) with distance 2\n- (2,1) with distance 3\n- (2,2) with distance 4\nThus, the 3 highest ranked items in the price range are (0,1), (1,1), and (2,1).\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example2drawio1.png]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,2,0,1],[1,3,3,1],[0,2,5,1]], pricing = [2,3], start = [2,3], k = 2\nOutput: [[2,1],[1,2]]\nExplanation: You start at (2,3).\nWith a price range of [2,3], we can take items from (0,1), (1,1), (1,2) and (2,1).\nThe ranks of these items are:\n- (2,1) with distance 2, price 2\n- (1,2) with distance 2, price 3\n- (1,1) with distance 3\n- (0,1) with distance 4\nThus, the 2 highest ranked items in the price range are (2,1) and (1,2).\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n[[img:leetcode_seed/assets/problems/2146-k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/2146-example3.png]]\n\nInput: grid = [[1,1,1],[0,0,1],[2,3,4]], pricing = [2,3], start = [0,0], k = 3\nOutput: [[2,1],[2,0]]\nExplanation: You start at (0,0).\nWith a price range of [2,3], we can take items from (2,0) and (2,1). \nThe ranks of these items are: \n- (2,1) with distance 5\n- (2,0) with distance 6\nThus, the 2 highest ranked items in the price range are (2,1) and (2,0). \nNote that k = 3 but there are only 2 reachable items within the price range.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `m == grid.length`\n\n- `n == grid[i].length`\n\n- `1 <= m, n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `1 <= m * n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= grid[i][j] <= 10⁵`\n\n- `pricing.length == 2`\n\n- `2 <= low <= high <= 10⁵`\n\n- `start.length == 2`\n\n- `0 <= row <= m - 1`\n\n- `0 <= col <= n - 1`\n\n- `grid[row][col] > 0`\n\n- `1 <= k <= m * n`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/k-highest-ranked-items-within-a-price-range/","problemName":"K Highest Ranked Items Within a Price Range","problemNumber":2146,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"s