t: finalSum = 12\nOutput: [2,4,6]\nExplanation: The following are valid splits: (12), (2 + 10), (2 + 4 + 6), and (4 + 8).\n(2 + 4 + 6) has the maximum number of integers, which is 3. Thus, we return [2,4,6].\nNote that [2,6,4], [6,2,4], etc. are also accepted.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: finalSum = 7\nOutput: []\nExplanation: There are no valid splits for the given finalSum.\nThus, we return an empty array.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: finalSum = 28\nOutput: [6,8,2,12]\nExplanation: The following are valid splits: (2 + 26), (6 + 8 + 2 + 12), and (4 + 24). \n(6 + 8 + 2 + 12) has the maximum number of integers, which is 4. Thus, we return [6,8,2,12].\nNote that [10,2,4,12], [6,2,4,16], etc. are also accepted.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= finalSum <= 10¹⁰`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-split-of-positive-even-integers/","problemName":"Maximum Split of Positive Even Integers","problemNumber":2178,"problemSlug":"maximum-split-of-positive-even-integers","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2178,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Divide and Conquer","Binary Indexed Tree","Segment Tree","Merge Sort","Ordered Set"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given two **0-indexed** arrays `nums1` and `nums2` of length `n`, both of which are **permutations** of `[0, 1, ..., n - 1]`.\n\nA **good triplet** is a set of `3` **distinct** values which are present in **increasing order** by position both in `nums1` and `nums2`. In other words, if we consider `pos1v` as the index of the value `v` in `nums1` and `pos2v` as the index of the value `v` in `nums2`, then a good triplet will be a set `(x, y, z)` where `0 <= x, y, z <= n - 1`, such that `pos1x < pos1y < pos1z` and `pos2x < pos2y < pos2z`.\n\nReturn *the **total number** of good triplets*.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: nums1 = [2,0,1,3], nums2 = [0,1,2,3]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: \nThere are 4 triplets (x,y,z) such that pos1x < pos1y < pos1z. They are (2,0,1), (2,0,3), (2,1,3), and (0,1,3). \nOut of those triplets, only the triplet (0,1,3) satisfies pos2x < pos2y < pos2z. Hence, there is only 1 good triplet.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: nums1 = [4,0,1,3,2], nums2 = [4,1,0,2,3]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: The 4 good triplets are (4,0,3), (4,0,2), (4,1,3), and (4,1,2).","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == nums1.length == nums2.length`\n\n- `3 <= n <= 10⁵`\n\n- `0 <= nums1[i], nums2[i] <= n - 1`\n\n- `nums1` and `nums2` are permutations of `[0, 1, ..., n - 1]`.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Binary Search","Divide and Conquer","Binary Indexed Tree","Segment Tree","Merge Sort","Ordered Set"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given two **0-indexed** arrays `nums1` and `nums2` of length `n`, both of which are **permutations** of `[0, 1, ..., n - 1]`.\n\nA **good triplet** is a set of `3` **distinct** values which are present in **increasing order** by position both in `nums1` and `nums2`. In other words, if we consider `pos1v` as the index of the value `v` in `nums1` and `pos2v` as the index of the value `v` in `nums2`, then a good triplet will be a set `(x, y, z)` where `0 <= x, y, z <= n - 1`, such that `pos1x < pos1y < pos1z` and `pos2x < pos2y < pos2z`.\n\nReturn *the **total number** of good triplets*.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [2,0,1,3], nums2 = [0,1,2,3]\nOutput: 1\nExplanation: \nThere are 4 triplets (x,y,z) such that pos1x < pos1y < pos1z. They are (2,0,1), (2,0,3), (2,1,3), and (0,1,3). \nOut of those triplets, only the triplet (0,1,3) satisfies pos2x < pos2y < pos2z. Hence, there is only 1 good triplet.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: nums1 = [4,0,1,3,2], nums2 = [4,1,0,2,3]\nOutput: 4\nExplanation: The 4 good triplets are (4,0,3), (4,0,2), (4,1,3), and (4,1,2).\